Here’s a categorized and alphabetically sorted list of 100 common English proverbs along with their meanings.

A. Wisdom & Learning (Life Lessons)
A bad workman always blames his tools. – People blame external factors for their failures.
A fool and his money are soon parted. – Foolish people easily lose their money.
A journey of a thousand miles begins with a single step. – Big achievements start with small efforts.
A leopard cannot change its spots. – People don’t change their fundamental nature.
A little knowledge is a dangerous thing. – Knowing something but not fully understanding it can lead to problems.
A rolling stone gathers no moss. – Constant movement prevents success or responsibility.
A stitch in time saves nine. – Solving a small problem early prevents bigger issues.
All good things must come to an end. – Nothing lasts forever.
All that glitters is not gold. – Appearances can be deceptive.
Better safe than sorry. – It’s wiser to be cautious than to regret later.
Experience is the best teacher. – Learning from real-life experiences is the most effective way.
If the shoe fits, wear it. – If something applies to you, accept it.
It is never too late to learn. – Learning can happen at any age.
Knowledge is power. – Education and information give people influence.
Practice makes perfect. – Repeated practice leads to improvement.
The pen is mightier than the sword. – Words and ideas have greater influence than violence.
There is no smoke without fire. – Rumors usually have some truth behind them.
What’s done is done. – The past cannot be changed.
When in Rome, do as the Romans do. – Adapt to local customs when in a different place.
Where there’s a will, there’s a way. – Determination can overcome obstacles.
B. Hard Work & Success
A bird in the hand is worth two in the bush. – It’s better to keep what you have than to risk losing it for something uncertain.
A penny saved is a penny earned. – Saving money is just as valuable as earning it.
Actions speak louder than words. – What you do is more important than what you say.
An idle mind is the devil’s workshop. – Doing nothing leads to trouble.
Early to bed and early to rise makes a man healthy, wealthy, and wise. – A disciplined routine leads to success.
Fortune favors the bold. – Brave actions bring success.
Genius is 1% inspiration and 99% perspiration. – Hard work is more important than talent.
Hard work never goes unrewarded. – Effort leads to success.
Honesty is the best policy. – Being truthful is always the best approach.
Never put off until tomorrow what you can do today. – Avoid procrastination.
No pain, no gain. – Hard work is necessary for success.
Opportunity knocks but once. – Don’t miss good chances because they may not come again.
Rome wasn’t built in a day. – Great things take time.
Slow and steady wins the race. – Consistency leads to success.
The early bird catches the worm. – Being proactive leads to success.
The harder you work, the luckier you get. – Success comes from effort.
Time is money. – Wasting time is like wasting money.
Well begun is half done. – Starting well makes finishing easier.
When the going gets tough, the tough get going. – Strong people keep working hard in difficult times.
You reap what you sow. – Your actions determine your results.
C. Relationships & Social Wisdom
A friend in need is a friend indeed. – True friends help in difficult times.
A house divided against itself cannot stand. – Unity is necessary for success.
Blood is thicker than water. – Family ties are stronger than friendships.
Charity begins at home. – Kindness should start with those closest to you.
Don’t bite the hand that feeds you. – Don’t hurt those who help you.
Don’t cry over spilled milk. – Don’t stress over something that can’t be changed.
Don’t judge a book by its cover. – Don’t judge by appearance alone.
Every cloud has a silver lining. – There is hope in every bad situation.
Love is blind. – Love makes people overlook flaws.
Misery loves company. – Unhappy people like others to be unhappy too.
One good turn deserves another. – Kindness should be repaid with kindness.
Out of sight, out of mind. – People forget things that are not around.
The grass is always greener on the other side. – People always think others have it better.
Too many cooks spoil the broth. – Too many people involved in a task can ruin it.
Two heads are better than one. – Teamwork produces better results.
United we stand, divided we fall. – Strength comes from unity.
What goes around comes around. – Your actions will return to you, good or bad.
You can’t have your cake and eat it too. – You can’t enjoy two conflicting benefits.
You scratch my back, and I’ll scratch yours. – Help others, and they will help you.
Your actions determine your reputation. – How you act influences how people see you.
D. Nature & Fate
A watched pot never boils. – Things feel slower when you are impatient.
April showers bring May flowers. – Hard times lead to better days.
Don’t count your chickens before they hatch. – Don’t assume success before it happens.
Don’t put all your eggs in one basket. – Don’t depend on just one thing.
Every dog has its day. – Everyone gets a chance at success.
Haste makes waste. – Rushing leads to mistakes.
Lightning never strikes the same place twice. – Rare events don’t happen repeatedly.
Make hay while the sun shines. – Take advantage of good conditions.
Money doesn’t grow on trees. – Money is hard to earn.
Necessity is the mother of invention. – Problems inspire creativity.
No news is good news. – If you hear nothing, things are probably okay.
Silence is golden. – Being quiet is sometimes better than speaking.
The apple doesn’t fall far from the tree. – Children resemble their parents.
The squeaky wheel gets the grease. – The most vocal people get attention.
There’s no place like home. – Home is the best place to be.
